# `is null` / `is not null` for all null checks

Use the **null pattern** for every null check on reference types and `Nullable<T>`. Never use `== null` or `!= null`.

## Preferred

```csharp
if (tenant is null) throw new ArgumentNullException(nameof(tenant));
if (tenant is not null) Apply(tenant);

return value is not null
    ? Format(value)
    : "(none)";
```

## Avoid

```csharp
// Avoid
if (tenant == null) throw new ArgumentNullException(nameof(tenant));
if (tenant != null) Apply(tenant);
```

## Why

- `is null` cannot be silently overridden by an operator overload — `==` / `!=` can.
- Reads as English ("is null", "is not null"), which matches the project's preference for clear guard clauses.
- Slimmer subset of **`CSharp-Terse-02-PatternMatching.mdc`** focused only on the most common case so it can be enforced independently.

## Scope

- Applies everywhere: assignments, conditions, ternaries, LINQ predicates, switch arms.
- Combine with the same-line guard rule (**`CSharp-Terse-01-GuardClausesSameLine.mdc`**) for one-line null guards.
